qjiw4/account_center_self_hosted_oidc"},{"short_id":"zevrur","created_at":"2026-05-22T12:36:14.000-05:00","title":"End-to-End Procedural Generation in Caves of Qud (2019)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jV-DZqdKlnE","score":10,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"\u003cp\u003eIn this 2019 GDC Math for Game Developers session, Freehold Games' Brian Bucklew \u0026amp; Jason Grinblat do an end-to-end walk-through of the systems used to generate villages in Caves of Qud, which include their own histories, cultures, architectural styles, storytelling traditions, NPCs, and quests.\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"In this 2019 GDC Math for Game Developers session, Freehold Games' Brian Bucklew \u0026 Jason Grinblat do an end-to-end walk-through of the systems used to generate villages in Caves of Qud, which include their own histories, cultures, architectural styles, storytelling traditions, NPCs, and quests.","submitter_user":"matt-y","user_is_author":false,"tags":["games","video"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/zevrur","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/zevrur/end_end_procedural_generation_caves_qud"},{"short_id":"xgwq0o","created_at":"2026-05-22T12:21:49.000-05:00","title":"Burnout in Open Source: A Structural Problem We Can Fix Together","url":"https://opensourcepledge.com/blog/burnout-in-open-source-a-structural-problem-we-can-fix-together/","score":6,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"pushcx","user_is_author":false,"tags":["culture"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/xgwq0o","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/xgwq0o/burnout_open_source_structural_problem"},{"short_id":"hkmhzi","created_at":"2026-05-22T11:12:46.000-05:00","title":"The case against boolean logic","url":"https://abuseofnotation.github.io/boolean-thinking/","score":-1,"flags":3,"comment_count":3,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"dhruvp","user_is_author":false,"tags":["logiclangs"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/hkmhzi","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/hkmhzi/case_against_boolean_logic"},{"short_id":"opxdzj","created_at":"2026-05-22T08:49:37.000-05:00","title":"LLM-powered Ascii web-game","url":"https://asciidia.com","score":0,"flags":2,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"wherewhy","user_is_author":false,"tags":["games","vibecoding"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/opxdzj","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/opxdzj/llm_powered_ascii_web_game"},{"short_id":"k96psg","created_at":"2026-05-22T08:22:52.000-05:00","title":"WordPress 7.0","url":"https://wordpress.org/download/releases/7-0/","score":8,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"\u003cp\u003eAn interesting release, for better or worse it includes access to AI tooling. Some of the block management and performance improvements around not loading resources looks like a step in the right direction.\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"An interesting release, for better or worse it includes access to AI tooling. Some of the block management and performance improvements around not loading resources looks like a step in the right direction.","submitter_user":"ndegruchy","user_is_author":false,"tags":["release","web"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/k96psg","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/k96psg/wordpress_7_0"},{"short_id":"gfjzwa","created_at":"2026-05-22T07:16:10.000-05:00","title":"The Maintainer's Dilemma","url":"https://spf13.com/p/the-maintainers-dilemma/","score":14,"flags":2,"comment_count":10,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"telemachus","user_is_author":false,"tags":["vibecoding"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/gfjzwa","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/gfjzwa/maintainer_s_dilemma"},{"short_id":"1acyon","created_at":"2026-05-22T06:47:46.000-05:00","title":"A Forth-inspired language for writing websites","url":"https://robida.net/entries/2026/05/21/a-forth-inspired-language-for-writing-websites","score":39,"flags":0,"comment_count":14,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"EvanHahn","user_is_author":false,"tags":["concatenative","web"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/1acyon","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/1acyon/forth_inspired_language_for_writing"},{"short_id":"pi9gjl","created_at":"2026-05-22T06:21:53.000-05:00","title":"score by collisions, patch by panic","url":"https://blog.himanshuanand.com/2026/05/score-by-collisions-patch-by-panic/","score":-1,"flags":5,"comment_count":0,"description":"\u003cp\u003eHello All\nI am the author of this post.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eA couple of weeks ago, my previous piece ('The 90 day disclosure policy is dead')\nended up here (\u003ca href=\"https://lobste.rs/s/qxkdgl/90_day_disclosure_policy_is_dead\" rel=\"ugc\"\u003ehttps://lobste.rs/s/qxkdgl/90_day_disclosure_policy_is_dead\u003c/a\u003e). The thread had some good comments specifically the critique that 'saying the model is broken is a complaint, not a proposal.'\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThat was completely fair feedback, So I wrote this followup specifically to address the questions raised in that Lobsters thread. It is an informal engineering RFC moving past the complaint and focusing on the defensive architecture we actually have to adopt right now (eg. default deny network egress, ephemeral containers to break persistence and rootless runtimes).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI also directly answered a few of the hardest questions from the last thread at the bottom of the post. I am submitting it here as I would appreciate the same level of  honest feedback on these architectural proposals.\nWhere do these circuit breakers fail in your production pipelines?\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"Hello All \r\nI am the author of this post.\r\n\r\nA couple of weeks ago, my previous piece ('The 90 day disclosure policy is dead') \r\nended up here (https://lobste.rs/s/qxkdgl/90_day_disclosure_policy_is_dead). The thread had some good comments specifically the critique that 'saying the model is broken is a complaint, not a proposal.'\r\n\r\nThat was completely fair feedback, So I wrote this followup specifically to address the questions raised in that Lobsters thread. It is an informal engineering RFC moving past the complaint and focusing on the defensive architecture we actually have to adopt right now (eg. default deny network egress, ephemeral containers to break persistence and rootless runtimes).\r\n\r\nI also directly answered a few of the hardest questions from the last thread at the bottom of the post. I am submitting it here as I would appreciate the same level of  honest feedback on these architectural proposals. \r\nWhere do these circuit breakers fail in your production pipelines?","submitter_user":"unknownhad","user_is_author":true,"tags":["practices"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/pi9gjl","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/pi9gjl/score_by_collisions_patch_by_panic"},{"short_id":"qwytbf","created_at":"2026-05-22T04:48:59.000-05:00","title":"Secure Boot and CA Rollover - a heads-up for distributions","url":"https://blog.einval.com/2026/05/22#secure_boot_ca_rollover","score":16,"flags":0,"comment_count":2,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"Foxboron","user_is_author":false,"tags":["linux","security"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/qwytbf","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/qwytbf/secure_boot_ca_rollover_heads_up_for"}]